In a sequel to #39977, I have found another bug in my original code for this challenge: when my `remove` method was passed an element that was present in the list but wasn't the list's `head`, it would remove every node from `head.next` through the node containing that element. I was using a `while` loop with `currentNode` and `previousNode` variables but was forgetting to update `previousNode` at the end of the loop, so when it found the element, it would link `head` all the way to `currentNode.next` no matter how far it had traveled.

Anyway, here's an update to test #&zwnj;4 ("Your <code>remove</code> method should reassign the reference of the previous node of the removed node to the removed node&apos;s <code>next</code> reference.") that'll catch mistakes like mine in the future, by having the test remove the third node of four in the list instead of the second node of three.

### Updated test:

```js
assert(
  (function () {
    var test = new LinkedList();

    test.add("cat");
    test.add("dog");
    test.add("snake");
    test.add("kitten");

    test.remove("snake");
    return test.head().next.next.element === "kitten";
  })()
);
```

-----

All tests are passing on my end. 👍🏼

```shell
freeCodeCamp % cd curriculum
curriculum % npm run test -- -g "Remove Elements from a Linked List"
...
  22 passing (5s)
```
